entry.title: shortcuts: Reset keyDisplay on key release
entry.content:
Problem:

1. Currently, when keyDisplay is set to an empty string (''), it

unexpectedly get set back later. Therefore, releasing key won't

reset keyDisplay.

2. When multiple keys are pressed, releasing the first key sets

keyDisplay to empty. However, releasing a second key changes

keyDisplay to that second key's value, which is not the intended

behavior.



Fix:

1. Use `updatedKeyEvent` to update keyDisplay and set

`pendingKeyEvent` to `updatedKeyEvent` afterwards.

2. Remove that condition where keyDisplay must match the previously

released key.

entry.content:
We switch blink FormControlsVerticalWritingModeDirectionSupport to

status experimental. This feature allows direction LTR and RTL to affect

how a form control with vertical writing-mode is rendered.



Currently, is implemented:

- If ltr, value is rendered top to bottom.

- If rtl, value is rendered bottom to top.

entry.title: DOMWindow: Set wrapper reference to global proxy object
entry.content:
The JS global proxy object already points to the

{Local,Remote}DOMWindow via internal field. Make

DOMWindow::main_world_wrapper_ point to the global proxy object as

well. Avoid using the already existing AssociateWithWrapper() methods

as they require that a context is properly set up.



{Local,Remote}WindowProxy's global_proxy_ field becomes a regular

traced reference without setting up the class id. The GC treats it

the same way for liveness but heap snapshot generation would not

consider it as a candidate to merge nodes with a JS object as it's not

ScriptWrappable's::main_world_wrapper_.



This way Wrappable/Wrapper pairs (represented by ScriptWrappable/V8

objects) are properly set up in the entire codebase and may on a

high-level considered as one object or "entity". This allows heap

snapshot generation to merge the nodes without considering the class

id state on the reference. Ultimately, this allows us to get rid of

the class id eventually and speed up all TracedReference creation.



Delete WPT test:

performance-timeline/tentative/performance-entry-source-deleted-frame.html



Rationale:

- The test was added to check that a PerformanceEntry does not leak

Window objects via its source property when PerformanceEntry objects

are stashed away to be consumed later.

- The test merely checks that we return a null Window for a detached

Window. This is not what it was added for.

- The test fails for FF and Safari [1]

- Writing this test properly is really hard: The JS wrapper is already

materialized in the iframe via `performance.mark()`. Thus accessing

`childEntry` from the main frame leaks the other iframe via the JS

wrapper constructor (that points to its context). In order to avoid

this, one must stash the Window itself in a weak ref, perform GC at

the event loop, and then check the weakref. Performing GC at the

event loop is not supported in WPT as of today.



[1] https://wpt.fyi/results/performance-timeline/tentative?label=master&label=experimental&aligned&q=performance-timeline%2Ftentative%2Fperformance-entry-source-deleted-frame.html

entry.title: [IntersectionOptimization] Fix crash with fixed-position when viewport is scrolled
entry.content:
A fixed-position element that is fixed to the viewport doesn't scroll

with the viewport, so if the root is the containing LayoutView, we

don't need to update intersection on viewport scroll. However,

previously CachedRects::unscrolled_unclipped_intersection_rect was

always in the scrolling contents coordinates making it depend on

viewport scroll position, and caused crashes when

IntersectionOptimization skipped intersection update on viewport

scroll.



Now let CachedRects::unscrolled_unclipped_intersection_rect be in the

root's border box space (i.e. viewport coordinates if the root is the

viewport) if the root doesn't scroll the target.

entry.title: Lacros-Test: Skip crosapi version check if already supported in ash.
entry.content:
This is a follow up cl for crrev.com/c/5117919.



Due to an issue with some tests improperly calling

BrowserInitParams::SetInitParamsForTests in test

Setup() which wipes out interceface_versions data

in BrowserInitParams, when IsTestControllerAvailable()

is called in browser_test_util to check if a TestControl

method is supported in ash, it failed incorrectly(the method is

available in all ash channels). This issue blocks another pending cl(crrev.com/c/5068434) since it calls browser_test_util::WaitForWindowCreation from

InProcessBrowserTest:: PreRunTestOnMainThread() and will

failed in IsTestControllerAvailable() for those tests which

wipes out BrowserInitParams::interface_versions by calling BrowserInitParams::SetInitParamsForTests. There

is already an ongoing effort to fix the root cause of

BrowserInitParams::SetInitParamsForTests issue, but it will

take some time to land that cl.



As a workaround to unblock crrev.com/c/5068434, this cl

removes the code for handling version skew if

the crosapi method already supported by all ash channels.

Instead, we validate if TestController is available in

LacrosService before calling crosapi. When test code calls

the apis in browser_test_utils to wait for UI elements to be

created in ash, ash should be available. If ash is not available

for some reason, it may expose some real problem to be fixed.

This should be handled differently than the cases in which

the crosapi is not supported in ash or the operation times out

(The existing code returns false for all these cases). Now the functions

fail with CHECK if ash is not available, and return false if crosapi

is not supported by ash or times out.



I patched crrev.com/c/5068434 with this cl and it passes CQ

run(crrev.com/c/5121452).

entry.title: [X11] Fix crash in PropertyCache when connection goes down
entry.content:
This fixes a potential CHECK failure in PropertyCache which has the

following code:

if (!it->second.response.has_value()) {

it->second.future.DispatchNow();

}

CHECK(it->second.response.has_value());

If the connection goes down, the CHECK will be triggered. The fix is

to change OnResponse() to eagerly dispatch the callback with a null

reply if the connection is down. This is similar to how Sync()

returns a null reply when the connection is down.

entry.title: [SharedImage] Change `needs_gl` checks to check READ || WRITE usages
entry.content:
Currently, various checks of whether a SharedImageUsage value indicates

that the SharedImage needs GL check for SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLES2 being

in the value. This effectively checks that SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLE2_READ

and SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLES2_WRITE are *both* specified. This is not

currently a problem as all clients always pass either both values or

neither value. However, in the future clients will sometimes pass one

or the other value. This CL changes these checks to check for *either*

SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLES2_READ *or* SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLES2_WRITE being

in the given SharedImageUsage.

entry.title: Add CHECK to AXPlatformNodeWin::InternalRelease to detect double-free
entry.content:
This CL adds a CHECK in AXPlatformNodeWin::InternalRelease that tests

whether the instance's memory can be freed from an external COM client. I think that it's possible in theory, but would like to see

some crashes in the wild to confirm it.



The theory is this:

1. An AXFragmentRootPlatformNodeWin ComPtr is created upon creation of

an AXFragmentRootWin (the member `platform_node_`). At that point, the

refcount is 1.

2. A COM client, presumably an assistive technology, gets a reference

to that ComPtr. The refcount at this point is 2.

3. The COM client releases the ComPtr more than once, mistakenly,

freeing the memory associated with this ComPtr. (refcount = 0)

4. Since `platform_node_` only gets nullified (ie., = nullptr) when

the AXFragmentRootWin is destroyed, the `platform_node_` is not nullptr

at line 5051 in AXPlatformNodeWin::Navigate, so we get into the `if`.

5. At line 5060, we try to access the memory in the pointer that got

freed and it crashes.



This CL introduces a new member `destroy_was_called_` only set to true

when AXPlatformNodeWin::Destroy (and therefore the subclass

AXFragmentRootPlatformNodeWin) is called. We set it before the ComPtr

is released again (see `Dispose`), so the CHECK should always pass if

the refcount only reaches 0 after the internal reference to the

platform node is nullified.

entry.title: Use WAL mode on UkmDatabase
entry.content:
This CL is switching the journal mode of segmentation database to

use WAL (Write-Ahead Logging). Instead of using a journal file

which contains a rollback with the original data (database-journal),

the database will have a Write-Ahead Logging which contains the modifications. Modifications are merge into the original on a snapshot.



see: Write-Ahead Logging (https://www.sqlite.org/wal.html)



The main advantage of using WAL is a reduction in the amount

of disk flushes by SQL write.

entry.title: [accessibility] Fix application of AXMode flags via AXPlatformNode
entry.content:

mode were collapsed into one. In so doing, a bug was introduced whereby

a change to the mode flags via ui::AXPlatformNode::NotifyAddAXModeFlags

was not propagated to active WebContents. This CL fixes that bug by

changing BrowserAccessibilityStateImpl so that it no longer relies on

the observation mechanism to handle calls to NotifyAddAXModeFlags, but

rather handles all modifications directly in its implementation of
